@node Before you start
@section Before you start

You need:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Emacs 27.1+} and @strong{Org 9.4+} (@samp{M-x org-version}).
@item
@samp{org-capture} bound to a key. This guide assumes the conventional
@code{C-c c}. If you have not bound it: @code{(global-set-key (kbd "C-c c") #'org-capture)}.
@item
@samp{org-agenda} bound to @code{C-c a} (the Org default).
@item
A directory to hold clients. The default is @samp{<org-directory>/clients}; this
guide uses @samp{~/org/clients}.
@end itemize

Throughout, the example client is @strong{Acme Corp} with the slug @samp{acme}.

@node Step 1 — Install and verify
@section Step 1 — Install and verify

@menu
* Install::
* Verify::
@end menu

@node Install
@subsection Install

With @samp{use-package} from a local clone:

@lisp
(use-package org-fractional-cto
  :load-path "~/src/org-fractional-cto"
  :after org
  :custom
  (org-fractional-cto-clients-directory "~/org/clients")
  (org-fractional-cto-author "Your Name")
  :config
  (org-fractional-cto-setup))
@end lisp

Or manually:

@lisp
(add-to-list 'load-path "~/src/org-fractional-cto")
(require 'org-fractional-cto)
(setq org-fractional-cto-clients-directory "~/org/clients")
(org-fractional-cto-setup)
@end lisp

@samp{org-fractional-cto-setup} does three things: installs the @samp{e} capture group,
registers the dashboard agenda command, and adds your existing client
directories to @samp{org-agenda-files}. It is @strong{idempotent} — safe to run again any
time (e.g. after you edit @samp{org-fractional-cto-dashboard-blocks}). Re-running
refreshes the captures and the dashboard in place rather than duplicating them,
so @code{M-x org-fractional-cto-setup} is the way to apply config changes without
restarting Emacs.

@node Verify
@subsection Verify

Three quick checks before you create anything:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Setup ran.} @code{M-x org-fractional-cto-setup} returns without error.
@item
@strong{Dashboard is registered.} Press @code{C-c a}. The dispatcher should list:
@samp{E   Fractional CTO — client dashboard}. (Press @samp{q} to dismiss.)
@item
@strong{Captures are installed.} Press @code{C-c c}. You should see
@samp{e   Engagement (select client)} in the menu. (Press @samp{C-g} to dismiss.)
@end enumerate

If all three pass, the package is live.

@node Step 2 — The two concepts you will lean on
@section Step 2 — The two concepts you will lean on

Before onboarding, understand the two ideas the whole workflow rests on.

@menu
* The active client::
* The client hub::
@end menu

@node The active client
@subsection The active client

Almost everything is scoped to one client at a time. Instead of a key prefix
per client, you set an @strong{active client} once per session and every capture and
the dashboard follow it.

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Command
@tab Effect
@item @samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-set-active-client}
@tab Pick the client for this session
@item @samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-clear-active-client}
@tab Go back to being prompted per capture
@item @samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-switch-client}
@tab Set active @strong{and} open its dashboard
@end multitable

With an active client set, @code{C-c c e ...} and @code{C-c a E} never prompt. With none
set, they prompt you to choose — nothing breaks, it is just one extra step.

@node The client hub
@subsection The client hub

Each client owns a directory with three files:

@example
~/org/clients/
  acme/
    acme.org      ← operational hub: one section per capture type
    standup.org   ← per-client standup template (the es capture reads this)
    CONTEXT.md    ← domain glossary, people, tech stack (load in AI sessions)
@end example

The hub's section headings, the capture targets, and the dashboard's queries
are all generated from a single section list, so they agree by construction —
you never wire a capture to a heading by hand.

@node Step 3 — Onboard your first client
@section Step 3 — Onboard your first client

Run:

@example
M-x org-fractional-cto-new-client
@end example


You are asked for two things:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Client name (display)} — e.g. @samp{Acme Corp}. Becomes the file @samp{#+title}, the
top-level heading, and the agenda @samp{:CATEGORY:}. (The @samp{#+AUTHOR} line is set
separately from @samp{org-fractional-cto-author}.)
@item
@strong{Client slug} — e.g. @samp{acme}. Lowercase, no spaces; it names the directory
and files, and is upper-cased into the Org tag (@samp{acme} → @samp{:ACME:};
non-alphanumerics become @samp{_}, so @samp{acme-eu} → @samp{:ACME_EU:}).
@end enumerate

The command then creates @samp{acme/acme.org}, @samp{acme/standup.org}, and
@samp{acme/CONTEXT.md}, adds the new directory to @samp{org-agenda-files} immediately (no
restart), and opens @samp{CONTEXT.md} for you to fill in.

@menu
* Walk the hub it generated::
@end menu

@node Walk the hub it generated
@subsection Walk the hub it generated

Open @samp{acme/acme.org}. At the top is a @samp{#+TODO} line defining the workflow's
states:

@example
#+TODO: TODO NEXT INPROGRESS WAITING | DONE CANCELLED
@end example

(Note @samp{INPROGRESS} has no hyphen — that is deliberate; see @ref{Troubleshooting}.)
This line is a convenience, not a requirement: @samp{org-fractional-cto-setup} already
registers the same keyword sequence into the global @samp{org-todo-keywords}, so the
states work in any buffer even before you open a hub. The per-file line just
means a hub still cycles correctly on a machine where setup never ran.

Below the top-level @samp{* Acme Corp Engagement  :ACTIVE:} heading is one @samp{**} section
per capture type — @samp{Actions}, @samp{Delegations}, @samp{Blockers}, @samp{People}, @samp{Commitments},
@samp{Risks}, @samp{Meeting Notes}, …, @samp{Retrospectives} — each tagged with only its type
subtag (e.g. @samp{** Delegations  :DELEGATED:}). The client identity is declared once
at file level via @samp{#+filetags: :ACME:} and is inherited by every heading — so
captures never carry a redundant per-item client tag. You do not edit these by
hand; captures file into them. Seeing the whole engagement in one outline is the
point — fold with @samp{overview}, expand the section you need.

@node Step 3b — Capture a prospect (pre-sales)
@section Step 3b — Capture a prospect (pre-sales)

A prospect is just a client at an earlier stage. Before an engagement is won you
still want to capture calls, do research, and track follow-ups — and the
dashboard already does that. Onboard a prospect with:

@example
M-x org-fractional-cto-new-prospect
@end example


It scaffolds the same hub as a client but stamps the engagement heading with the
@samp{LEAD} stage tag, sets the prospect active, and opens the @strong{pre-sales call}
capture (@samp{el}) so you record the conversation immediately. From there:

@itemize
@item
@samp{C-c c el} — capture each pre-sales call (the ask, pain, signals, next step).
@item
@samp{C-c c eo} — log research findings as you learn about the company, market, and
tech. Fold the durable facts into @samp{CONTEXT.md}.
@item
@samp{C-c c eF} — record a fit / qualification verdict (Pursue / Hold / Pass).
@item
@samp{C-c c ew} / @samp{eg} / @samp{eb} — ordinary actions, delegations, and blockers work
here too, so your pre-sales follow-ups land on the dashboard like any work.
@end itemize

As the prospect advances, move the stage with @samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-set-stage}
(@samp{LEAD} → @samp{QUALIFIED} → @samp{ACTIVE} when you win, or @samp{LOST}). Across all clients,
@samp{C-c a P} shows the whole pipeline — every @samp{LEAD} / @samp{QUALIFIED} engagement, one
line each.

If you have hubs created before stages existed, run @samp{M-x
org-fractional-cto-upgrade-hub} on each to add the new sections and an @samp{ACTIVE}
stage tag.

@node Step 4 — Fill in CONTEXTmd
@section Step 4 — Fill in CONTEXT.md

@samp{CONTEXT.md} is the human (and AI) brief for the engagement. It opens
automatically after onboarding, pre-populated with section headers:

@itemize
@item
@strong{What We're Building} — one paragraph on the product and the mandate.
@item
@strong{Domain Vocabulary} — the terms the team uses; the highest-leverage section.
@item
@strong{Tech Stack} — as known at onboarding.
@item
@strong{Key People} — client side and your side.
@item
@strong{Active Work Streams} and @strong{Current Priorities}.
@end itemize

Fill at least vocabulary, people, and priorities now; the rest accretes. If you
do hands-on implementation with an AI agent, load this file at the start of each
session so the agent speaks the client's language. It is plain Markdown so it
travels into any tool.

@node Step 5 — Set the active client
@section Step 5 — Set the active client

Back from @samp{CONTEXT.md}:

@example
M-x org-fractional-cto-set-active-client
@end example


Choose @samp{acme}. The echo area confirms @samp{Active client: acme}. From here, every
capture and the dashboard target Acme with no prompting.

@itemize
@item
@samp{org-fractional-cto-clear-active-client} returns to per-capture prompting.
@item
@samp{org-fractional-cto-switch-client} sets a @strong{different} client active and opens
its dashboard in one step — the fast path when you change context.
@end itemize

The active client is per-session state; it resets when Emacs restarts. Set it
once when you sit down to work on a client.

@node Step 6 — Your first capture in detail
@section Step 6 — Your first capture, in detail

Capture an action. Press @code{C-c c e w}:

@enumerate
@item
@code{C-c c} opens org-capture; @samp{e} selects the engagement group; @samp{w} selects
@strong{Action item}.
@item
You are prompted for the action text, then a deadline.
@item
Org files a @samp{TODO} under Acme's @samp{Actions} section, stamped with the creation
time, and @strong{clocks in} (the @samp{ew} template sets @samp{:clock-in}). The client tag
@samp{:ACME:} is inherited from @samp{#+filetags} — it does not appear on the item itself.
The capture template also auto-fills the client display name (no @samp{Client:} prompt).
@item
Finish with @code{C-c C-c} to file it (which also clocks out), or @code{C-c C-k} to
abort.
@end enumerate

Open @samp{acme.org} and confirm the new @samp{TODO} sits under @samp{** Actions}. That round
trip — pick a key, answer the prompts, it lands in the right section already
tagged — is the entire capture model. Two things make it work:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Routing.} Each template targets a section heading by name in the active
client's hub. No inbox, no manual refiling.
@item
@strong{Two kinds of template.} Short captures (action, risk, commitment, …) are
inline; richer ones (discovery, ADR, QBR, …) are filled from a file in the
bundled @samp{templates/} folder, which you can override (see @ref{Step 11 — Make it yours, , Step 11}). The
@strong{standup} (@samp{es}) is special: it reads the client's own @samp{standup.org} so you can
tailor the streams to the real team, falling back to the bundled template.
@end itemize

