@menu
* Acting on an action that already exists::
@end menu

@node Acting on an action that already exists
@subsubsection Acting on an action that already exists

@samp{ew}, @samp{eg} and @samp{eb} all @strong{create} an item. Two commands instead act on the Org
heading already under your cursor, so you never retype work that is already
captured:

@itemize
@item
@samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-delegate-at-point} — hand off the action at point. It
flips the heading to @samp{WAITING}, adds the @samp{DELEGATED} tag, records who now owns
it (@samp{ASSIGNED_TO}) and when (@samp{DELEGATED_ON}), and schedules your follow-up
check-in (@samp{SCHEDULED}), optionally with a delivery @samp{DEADLINE}. It is @samp{eg}
applied in place — the action moves from @strong{Open actions} to @strong{Delegated —
awaiting response} on the next dashboard refresh.
@item
@samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-block-at-point} — raise a blocker against the action
at point. It files a @samp{[#A]} blocker into the client's @strong{Blockers} section with
its @samp{BLOCKING} property linked back to the action, and drops a back-reference
under the action itself, so the two sides point at each other.
@end itemize

Both are bound to @samp{g} and @samp{b} in @samp{org-fractional-cto-command-map} (see
@ref{Step 10 — The management commands, , Step 10}). They can also be invoked
@strong{directly on an agenda line} — Evil users get @samp{, g} (delegate) and @samp{, b} (block)
in the agenda's motion state; non-Evil users can set
@samp{org-fractional-cto-agenda-keymap-prefix} for a prefix key, or use @samp{M-x}.
Reach for these when the work is already on a heading; reach for @samp{eg} / @samp{eb} when
you are capturing something new.

