— no extra configuration needed.
@item
@strong{Non-Evil users}: set @samp{org-fractional-cto-agenda-keymap-prefix} to a prefix key
(e.g. @samp{"C-c C-'"}) for prefix access; otherwise reach them via @samp{M-x}.
@end itemize

@node File Organization
@section File Organization

The package ships the templates and these guides; your engagements live in
@samp{org-fractional-cto-clients-directory} (default @samp{<org-directory>/clients}).

The package (shareable, read-only to you):

@example
org-fractional-cto/
  org-fractional-cto.el          ← core: state, paths, keymap, setup
  org-fractional-cto-capture.el  ← the `e' capture group
  org-fractional-cto-agenda.el   ← the C-c a E dashboard
  org-fractional-cto-scaffold.el ← new-client onboarding
  templates/                     ← bundled capture templates (override-able)
    client_meeting.org adr.org discovery.org delegation.org blocker.org
    weekly_review.org retrospective.org standup.org ... etc.
  doc/
    playbook.org                 ← phases, hat model, decision frameworks
    reference.org                ← this file
  README.org                     ← install + manual + legend
@end example

Your engagements (yours, version-controlled separately):

@example
<clients-directory>/
  acme/                ← created by M-x org-fractional-cto-new-client
    acme.org           ← ★ OPERATIONAL HUB: all captures land here directly
    standup.org        ← per-client standup template (tailor the streams)
    CONTEXT.md         ← domain vocab, key people, stack (load in AI sessions)
  globex/
    globex.org
    standup.org
    CONTEXT.md
@end example

A non-client inbox (@samp{refile.org} or your @samp{org-default-notes-file}) still holds
generic captures (@samp{t}, @samp{n}, @samp{m}); engagement captures bypass it entirely.

@menu
* The capture flow::
* The lookup flow::
@end menu

@node The capture flow
@subsection The capture flow

Client captures go @strong{directly} to the relevant section of @samp{<client>.org} via
@samp{file+headline} — no inbox step, no refiling needed. Open @samp{<client>.org} (or any
client file) to see everything that has been captured for that account, organised
by section.

@samp{refile.org} is still the inbox for @strong{non-client} captures (generic todos, notes,
meeting entries via the @samp{t}, @samp{n}, @samp{m} keys). The discipline of clearing it still
applies, but client work bypasses it entirely.

@node The lookup flow
@subsection The lookup flow

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Agenda dashboard} — @samp{C-c a E} opens the @strong{global} dashboard spanning all
clients: 7-day agenda, delegated items awaiting response, blockers & escalations,
open actions, commitments with deadlines, active risks, security findings, tech
debt, and pending scope decisions. This is the daily starting point. When an
active client is set, the view opens pre-focused on that client via the native
tag filter (@samp{CATEGORY} column shows each entry's client). Use @samp{/} to widen,
refocus, or clear the filter.
@item
@strong{Browse by section} — @samp{C-x C-f <client>.org} then navigate headings (@samp{C-c C-n/p}
to move between headings, @samp{S-TAB} to collapse/expand). Each section contains
all captures of that type in reverse-chronological order.
@item
@strong{Tag search} — @samp{C-c a m TAGNAME} to find entries across all agenda files by tag
(e.g. @samp{RISK}, @samp{COMMITMENT}, @samp{TECHDEBT}).
@item
@strong{Full-text search} — @samp{C-c a s} to search across all agenda files by keyword.
@item
@strong{org-roam} — @samp{M-x org-roam-node-find} for the longer-form reference docs
(role plan, system discovery).
@end enumerate

@node Capture Templates — Complete Reference
@section Capture Templates — Complete Reference

All engagement templates use the pattern: @samp{C-c c e<key>}. Captures file @strong{directly}
to the relevant section of the active client's @samp{<client>.org} (set the active
client with @samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-set-active-client} to avoid being prompted each time).
The client display name is auto-filled from the hub's @samp{#+title} — no @samp{Client:}
prompt appears. Clocked entries start the org-clock automatically.

@menu
* Relationship & Communication Templates::
* Action Tracking & Delegation Templates::
* Risk & Delivery Templates::
* Technical Templates::
@end menu

@node Relationship & Communication Templates
@subsection Relationship & Communication Templates

@menu
* @samp{es} — Standup Notes::
* @samp{em} — Client Meeting::
* @samp{ei} — Internal Sync::
* @samp{ep} — Stakeholder Profile::
* @samp{ec} — Commitment Captured::
* @samp{eh} — Client Health Check::
* @samp{eq} — QBR (Quarterly Business Review)::
@end menu

@node @samp{es} — Standup Notes
@subsubsection @samp{es} — Standup Notes

@emph{Use:} Attending any team standup. One capture per session you attend.
@emph{Clock:} Yes — tracks time spent in standups.
@emph{Fields:} Date (auto), client name.
@emph{Structure:} Per-team sections (Shipped / Next / Blockers) + Actions/Escalations.
@emph{After capturing:} Scan for any blocker that needs a risk entry (@samp{er}) or
commitment capture (@samp{ec}). Refile to client's discovery or ops folder.

@node @samp{em} — Client Meeting
@subsubsection @samp{em} — Client Meeting

@emph{Use:} Any call or meeting with the client — planning, status, ad hoc.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Meeting title, client attendees, our attendees.
@emph{Structure:} Agenda → Discussion → Decisions → Commitments (both sides) → Actions → Follow-up deadline.
@emph{After capturing:} Immediately capture any commitments (@samp{ec}). Send written
summary to client within 2 hours. Never let a meeting end without a follow-up
summary — this is how trust is built.

@node @samp{ei} — Internal Sync
@subsubsection @samp{ei} — Internal Sync

@emph{Use:} Weekly internal sync with team leads — always before client-facing comms.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Date, client name.
@emph{Structure:} Commitments vs. reality gap | Blockers to escalate | Risk updates |
Client comms review | Actions.
@emph{Rule:} Nothing surfaces to the client that hasn't passed through this sync first.

@node @samp{ep} — Stakeholder Profile
@subsubsection @samp{ep} — Stakeholder Profile

@emph{Use:} First time you meet or learn about a significant client contact. One profile
per person. Update it as the relationship develops.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Full name, role, organisation.
@emph{Key sections:} Their personal definition of success (not the project's) | Key
priorities & concerns | Communication preferences | Relationship status |
How to engage them effectively.
@emph{Why it matters:} Stakeholder maps decay fast. Documenting what makes each person
tick lets you tailor every communication.

@node @samp{ec} — Commitment Captured
@subsubsection @samp{ec} — Commitment Captured

@emph{Use:} Any time a commitment is made — by you @strong{or} by the client — in any meeting.
Capture it immediately, while still in the session.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Commitment description, due date (becomes a @samp{DEADLINE}), owner.
@emph{After capturing:} Refile to the commitment log in the client's document. Review
all open commitments at each internal sync.

@node @samp{eh} — Client Health Check
@subsubsection @samp{eh} — Client Health Check

@emph{Use:} Monthly. Three pulse questions sent to the client (or discussed in a call).
@emph{Fields:} Month, year.
@emph{Questions (built in):} What's working well? What would you change? What would you
love to see in the next 30 days?
@emph{After capturing:} Act on one specific thing from their feedback before next month.
The pattern of not acting on feedback is invisible until it's too late.

@node @samp{eq} — QBR (Quarterly Business Review)
@subsubsection @samp{eq} — QBR (Quarterly Business Review)

@emph{Use:} Quarterly formal checkpoint with client stakeholders.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Quarter, client attendees, our attendees.
@emph{Structure:} Deliverables table | Business impact | Technology roadmap review |
Strategic recommendation | Next quarter priorities | Renewal/expansion | Decisions
needed | Action items.
@emph{After capturing:} Send written summary within 24 hours. The written summary is
part of the ceremony — don't skip it.
@emph{Strategic recommendation:} Always include one recommendation they didn't ask for.
Frame it as business opportunity first, technology second. This is what separates
a vendor from a strategic partner.

@node Action Tracking & Delegation Templates
@subsection Action Tracking & Delegation Templates

@menu
* @samp{ew} — Action Item (quick TODO)::
* @samp{eg} — Delegate Action (WAITING)::
* @samp{eb} — Blocker / Escalation::
* Acting on an item that already exists (@samp{delegate-at-point}, @samp{block-at-point}): Acting on an item that already exists (@samp{delegate-at-point} @samp{block-at-point}). 
* @samp{eW} — Weekly Review::
* @samp{eP} — Person / Team Member Note::
@end menu

@node @samp{ew} — Action Item (quick TODO)
@subsubsection @samp{ew} — Action Item (quick TODO)

@emph{Use:} A task you're taking on yourself. The fast path for ad-hoc work.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Action description, due date (becomes a @samp{DEADLINE}).
@emph{After capturing:} Shows up in @samp{C-c a E} → "Open Actions". Re-prioritise as needed.

@node @samp{eg} — Delegate Action (WAITING)
@subsubsection @samp{eg} — Delegate Action (WAITING)

@emph{Use:} Any time you hand a task to a team member. This is the core delegation tool.
@emph{Fields:} Task, assignee (@samp{ASSIGNED_TO} property), expected delivery (@samp{DEADLINE}),
your check-in date (@samp{SCHEDULED}), success criteria.
@emph{Why WAITING:} The entry is created in the @samp{WAITING} state, not @samp{TODO}. This separates
"things I owe" from "things I'm owed" — they surface in the dedicated
"Delegated — Awaiting Response" block of @samp{C-c a E}.
@emph{After capturing:} The @samp{SCHEDULED} date is your follow-up trigger. If the check-in
passes with no update, escalate. Review every WAITING item at the Friday weekly review.
@emph{Discipline:} Delegation without a check-in date is hoping, not managing. Always set one.

@node @samp{eb} — Blocker / Escalation
@subsubsection @samp{eb} — Blocker / Escalation

@emph{Use:} The moment something is blocking delivery and you can't clear it yourself.
@emph{Fields:} What is blocked, what feature/stream it blocks (@samp{BLOCKING}), who can remove
it (@samp{UNBLOCK_OWNER}), root cause, options, escalation path, resolve-by deadline.
@emph{Priority:} Created as @samp{[#A] TODO}. Blockers are always top priority — they compound.
@emph{After capturing:} Surfaces in @samp{C-c a E} → "Blockers & Escalations". If unresolved by
the deadline, escalate via the named path (standup → internal sync → client).

@node Acting on an item that already exists (@samp{delegate-at-point} @samp{block-at-point})
@subsubsection Acting on an item that already exists (@samp{delegate-at-point}, @samp{block-at-point})

@samp{ew}, @samp{eg} and @samp{eb} @emph{create} entries. Two interactive commands act on the Org
heading already at point, so you never retype work that is already captured.

@itemize
@item
@samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-delegate-at-point} (@samp{g} in the command map) — the @samp{eg}
gesture applied in place. Sets the heading to @samp{WAITING}, adds the @samp{DELEGATED}
tag, records @samp{ASSIGNED_TO} and @samp{DELEGATED_ON}, and @samp{SCHEDULED=s your check-in;
  optionally sets a delivery =DEADLINE}. The item moves to the dashboard's
"Delegated — Awaiting Response" block. An assignee is required.
@item
@samp{M-x org-fractional-cto-block-at-point} (@samp{b} in the command map) — the @samp{eb}
gesture applied in place. Files a @samp{[#A]} blocker into the client's Blockers
section with @samp{BLOCKING} linked back to the action, and inserts a
back-reference under the action. Optional resolve-by @samp{DEADLINE}.
@end itemize

@emph{Discipline:} reach for these when the work is already on a heading; reach for
@samp{eg} / @samp{eb} when you are capturing something new. The back-link is an internal
@samp{[[*heading]]} link, so keep action headings distinctly named.

@node @samp{eW} — Weekly Review
@subsubsection @samp{eW} — Weekly Review

@emph{Use:} Friday, 15 minutes, before the week closes. Your delegation and team pulse review.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Week ending.
@emph{Structure:} Shipped this week | What slipped and why | Delegation inbox check-in
table | Blockers to escalate | Key decisions | Team pulse | Top 3 next week | Comms to send.
@emph{The discipline:} This is where you reconcile every WAITING item against reality.
Anyone who's gone quiet gets a direct ping — don't wait for the next standup.
@emph{After capturing:} Each "change/action needed" becomes a TODO@. Use @samp{C-c a E} delegated
block as the source of truth while filling the inbox table.

@node @samp{eP} — Person / Team Member Note
@subsubsection @samp{eP} — Person / Team Member Note

@emph{Use:} Capturing something about a team member — capacity, a concern, a win, a
development need. Builds the People section over time.
@emph{Fields:} Name, role/stream, @samp{STREAM} property.
@emph{Why it matters:} As a fractional CTO you're managing people you didn't hire and
don't see daily. Tracking capacity signals (who's overloaded, who's a single point
of failure) is how you spot delivery risk before it becomes a missed deadline.
@emph{Maintain:} The People section also holds the Team Roster and Stream → Lead map —
keep those current as the team changes.

@node Risk & Delivery Templates
@subsection Risk & Delivery Templates

@menu
* @samp{er} — Risk Item::
* @samp{ee} — Scope Change / Out-of-Scope Flag::
* @samp{ef} — Post-Mortem / Incident::
* @samp{eR} — Retrospective::
@end menu

@node @samp{er} — Risk Item
@subsubsection @samp{er} — Risk Item

@emph{Use:} Any new risk to the engagement or delivery — technical or otherwise.
Capture immediately when identified; don't wait for the next sync.
@emph{Fields:} Description, likelihood (High/Medium/Low), impact (High/Medium/Low), owner, mitigation.
@emph{After capturing:} Add to the risk register in the master discovery doc. Review
at every internal sync. A risk that sits in refile.org is not managed.

@node @samp{ee} — Scope Change / Out-of-Scope Flag
@subsubsection @samp{ee} — Scope Change / Out-of-Scope Flag

@emph{Use:} Any time you identify work that is outside the current SOW, or the client
asks for something that may be out of scope.
@emph{Fields:} Description, who identified it, SOW status (out/in/grey area).
@emph{Rule:} Never agree to out-of-scope work in a client meeting. Capture it here,
bring it through the internal sync, then respond to the client with a clear framing.
@emph{After capturing:} Internal sync review → commercial assessment → client response.

@node @samp{ef} — Post-Mortem / Incident
@subsubsection @samp{ef} — Post-Mortem / Incident

@emph{Use:} Any production incident, delivery failure, or significant quality issue.
@emph{Fields:} Incident title, date, severity, duration, what was affected.
@emph{Structure:} What happened | Root cause | How we fixed it | Was client notified? |
Prevention | Actions.
@emph{Timing:} Capture within 24 hours. The detail fades quickly.
@emph{Client communication:} "Here's what happened, here's what we did, here's what
we're doing to prevent recurrence." In that order.

@node @samp{eR} — Retrospective
@subsubsection @samp{eR} — Retrospective

@emph{Use:} End of each sprint or delivery cycle. Distinct from a post-mortem — a
retro is @strong{proactive and routine} (team process), a post-mortem is @strong{reactive} (a
failure). Run a retro whether or not anything went wrong.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Sprint/period, facilitator, attendees.
@emph{Structure:} Sprint goals vs. actuals (table) | What went well | What didn't go
well | What we'll change (owned, time-boxed) | Team health signals | Action items.
@emph{Pair with:} gstack @samp{/retro} as the facilitation prompt before or during the session.
@emph{After capturing:} Each "what we'll change" row becomes a TODO in the Actions section.
@emph{Discipline:} Focus on the system, not the person. "What process let this happen?"
not "who dropped this?" The retro is for improving how the team works, not assigning blame.

@node Technical Templates
@subsection Technical Templates

@menu
* @samp{ed} — Discovery Session::
* @samp{ea} — Architecture Decision Record (ADR)::
* @samp{eA} — Architecture Health Review::
* @samp{ev} — Vendor / Tool Evaluation::
* @samp{et} — Technical Debt Item::
* @samp{ex} — Security Finding::
* @samp{en} — Innovation Pipeline Idea::
@end menu

@node @samp{ed} — Discovery Session
@subsubsection @samp{ed} — Discovery Session

@emph{Use:} Structured conversation with any team lead to map their stream. One per stream.
@emph{Clock:} Yes — these are significant sessions.
@emph{Fields:} Team/role, client, attendees, focus area, stream name.
@emph{Structure:} Team context | Active workstreams (table) | Tech stack (table) |
Architecture & integrations | Pain points | Quality & testing | Deployment & ops |
Tech debt (table) | Security observations | Innovation opportunities | Open questions |
Follow-up actions.
@emph{Before the session:} Run @samp{/grill-me} (mattpocock/skills) to surface your assumptions.
@emph{After the session:} Refile immediately. Update cross-cutting sections of the master
discovery doc. Run a synthesis pass after every 2–3 sessions.

@node @samp{ea} — Architecture Decision Record (ADR)
@subsubsection @samp{ea} — Architecture Decision Record (ADR)

@emph{Use:} Any significant technology or architecture decision — things that are hard to
reverse, affect multiple streams, or have long-term cost implications.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Decision title, client, status (Proposed/Accepted/Deprecated/Superseded).
@emph{Structure:} Context (the forcing situation) | Decision (what and by whom) |
Alternatives considered | Trade-offs accepted | Consequences (positive/negative/risks) |
Review date.
@emph{Rule:} If you're spending more than 30 minutes deciding something, it warrants an ADR@.
A decision not documented is a decision that will be re-litigated.

@node @samp{eA} — Architecture Health Review
@subsubsection @samp{eA} — Architecture Health Review

@emph{Use:} Quarterly. A structured assessment of the full system's health.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Quarter, year, client, your name, teams reviewed.
@emph{Structure:} Scalability | Maintainability | Integration fragility | Dependency risk |
Technical debt table | Technology roadmap review | Recommendations | How to present.
@emph{Framing for the client:} "Transparency and forward planning" — never a problem list.
The goal is to demonstrate that you're ahead of issues, not behind them.

@node @samp{ev} — Vendor / Tool Evaluation
@subsubsection @samp{ev} — Vendor / Tool Evaluation

@emph{Use:} Assessing any new tool, platform, or technology vendor.
@emph{Clock:} Yes.
@emph{Fields:} Vendor name, client, category, evaluator.
@emph{Structure:} Problem being solved | Recommendation (with rationale) | Alternatives |
Assessment (solves the problem? build vs. buy? lock-in? data handling? 2-year TCO) |
Decision deadline.
@emph{Decision framework:} Commodity infrastructure → buy. Differentiating capability → build.
Anything that touches customer PII → scrutinise the vendor's data handling terms first.

@node @samp{et} — Technical Debt Item
@subsubsection @samp{et} — Technical Debt Item

@emph{Use:} Immediately when you identify tech debt — during discovery, code review,
architecture sessions, or standups.
@emph{Fields:} Description, area (Frontend/Backend/Infra/Integration/Data/Security),
severity (Critical/High/Medium/Low), discovery context, impact if unaddressed.
@emph{After capturing:} Add to the tech debt register in the master discovery doc.
Prioritise at the next architecture session. Debt that isn't visible isn't managed.

@node @samp{ex} — Security Finding
@subsubsection @samp{ex} — Security Finding

@emph{Use:} Any security or compliance observation — immediately when found.
@emph{Fields:} Finding description, severity, area (PCI/GDPR/API/Auth/Data/Infra),
current status (Open/Mitigated/Resolved/Accepted), recommended action, owner.
Closed-out findings (Resolved/Mitigated) drop off the dashboard's "Open security
findings" block — the same rule as the risk register.
@emph{Rule:} Critical findings surface to the internal sync before end of day.
High findings surface within 48 hours. Never downgrade severity to avoid a
difficult conversation.

@node @samp{en} — Innovation Pipeline Idea
@subsubsection @samp{en} — Innovation Pipeline Idea

@emph{Use:} Any time you spot something that could be done better, smarter, or that the
client doesn't yet know is possible. Capture without filtering — evaluate later.
@emph{Fields:} Title, category (AI/ML / Data / Platform / Integration / Music Tech / Other).
@emph{Structure:} The opportunity (business framing first) | The technology | Why now /
why this client | Rough effort | Next step.
@emph{Pipeline review:} Monthly — select one idea to develop into a brief. Present the
best one at each QBR as the "Strategic Recommendation."

@node Operating Rhythms — Day by Day
@section Operating Rhythms — Day by Day

@menu
* Daily::
* Weekly::
* Monthly::
* Quarterly::
@end menu

@node Daily
@subsection Daily

@example
Morning (15 min)
  └── Review refile.org inbox — refile or act on anything from yesterday
  └── Check open commitments and today's deadlines in agenda (C-c a a)
  └── Identify which hat today's sessions require

During day
  └── Attend standups → C-c c es (clock in)
  └── Capture risks, debt, security findings immediately when spotted
  └── Any client meeting → C-c c em + send summary within 2 hours

End of day (10 min)
  └── Refile today's captures from refile.org
  └── Any commitment made today → C-c c ec (if not already done)
  └── Anything that surfaced that needs to go to Monday's internal sync?
@end example

@node Weekly
@subsection Weekly

@example
Monday (internal sync first — then nothing client-facing until done)
  └── C-c c ei — internal sync
  └── Review: commitments vs. reality gap, risk register, blockers
  └── Decide: what goes to the client this week and how

Wednesday / Thursday (client sync)
  └── C-c c em — client meeting
  └── Send written summary within 2 hours
  └── Any commitments → C-c c ec immediately after

Friday (weekly close — 20 min)
  └── Clear refile.org inbox
  └── Review open commitments — anything at risk of missing deadline?
  └── One sentence in the discovery/ops doc Reflection log: what changed this week
@end example

@node Monthly
@subsection Monthly

@example
First week
  └── Client health check → C-c c eh
  └── Review open risks — anything escalating or resolved?
  └── Review innovation pipeline → pick one idea to develop into a brief

Third week
  └── Architecture review prep: review open ADRs, debt register, security findings
  └── Update technology roadmap if anything shifted
  └── Draft any discovery synthesis notes that have been accumulating
@end example

@node Quarterly
@subsection Quarterly

@example
End of quarter
  └── Architecture health review → C-c c eA
  └── QBR preparation: translate all delivery into business outcomes
  └── Select strategic recommendation for the QBR (from innovation pipeline)
  └── QBR session → C-c c eq
  └── Send QBR written summary within 24 hours
  └── Review: any scope expansion opportunity to progress next quarter?
@end example

@node The Hat Model in Practice
@section The Hat Model in Practice

Switching hats mid-session dilutes both. When you sit down to work, know which
hat you're wearing and stick to it for the duration of that block.

@menu
* Before any significant session::
* Hat descriptions::
@end menu

@node Before any significant session
@subsection Before any significant session

Run one of these first — it takes 5 minutes and prevents hours of rework:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Session type
@tab Run first
@tab Why
@item Discovery interview
@tab @samp{/grill-me}
@tab Surface what you're assuming; don't anchor the conversation to your frame
@item Architecture decision
@tab @samp{/office-hours}
@tab Challenge your own framing before committing
@item Client meeting (complex topic)
@tab @samp{/grill-with-docs} + SOW
@tab Verify you're solving the right problem
@item Starting implementation in an unfamiliar area
@tab @samp{/zoom-out}
@tab Map the system before touching it
@item Handoff between sessions
@tab @samp{/handoff}
